  "answer": "## Answer\nAutonomous agents optimize for **flexibility**: the model can choose its next step and tools at runtime. Workflow-based agents optimize for **control**: the path is predefined, so behavior is more predictable and easier to validate. Anthropic explicitly distinguishes these as different architectures, and recommends workflows for well-defined tasks and agents when flexible, model-driven decision-making is needed at scale. ([anthropic.com](https://www.anthropic.com/research/building-effective-agents/))\n\n**Main trade-offs:**\n- **Autonomous agents:** better on open-ended or changing tasks, but they usually add latency, cost, and operational risk because the system must reason, select tools, and recover from mistakes dynamically. ([anthropic.com](https://www.anthropic.com/research/building-effective-agents/))\n- **Workflow-based agents:** better for repeatable tasks, compliance, and debugging because the control flow is explicit; the downside is rigidity, and complex declarative flows can get cumbersome as branching increases. ([anthropic.com](https://www.anthropic.com/research/building-effective-agents/))\n- **Engineering effort:** workflow systems can be simpler to test and govern, while autonomous systems often require stronger guardrails, execution infrastructure, and careful tool design. ([openai.com](https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/))\n\nA practical rule from the sources is: **start with the simplest workflow that solves the problem, then add autonomy only when variability or scale justifies the extra complexity.** ([anthropic.com](https://www.anthropic.com/research/building-effective-agents/))\n\n## Sources\n- Anthropic, *Building Effective AI Agents*: https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/building-effective-agents. ([anthropic.com](https://www.anthropic.com/research/building-effective-agents/))\n- OpenAI, *A practical guide to building agents*: https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/. ([openai.com](https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/))\n- OpenAI, *From model to agent: Equipping the Responses API with a computer environment*: https://openai.com/index/equip-responses-api-computer-environment/. ([openai.com](https://openai.com/index/equip-responses-api-computer-environment))\n\n## Limitations\nThis is a synthesis of vendor engineering guidance, not a controlled benchmark comparison, so the exact trade-off depends on the task, toolset, and reliability requirements. Terminology also varies across vendors: some call both patterns \"agentic systems\" and separate them only by how much control the model has. ([anthropic.com](https://www.anthropic.com/research/building-effective-agents/))"
